 present. Drawn from the disciplines of history and political theory, the contributors to this volume engage in a mutually informing conversation about popular power. They conclude that the problems that first gave rise to popular sovereignty remain simultaneously compelling, unresolved and worthy of further attention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocratization. 0aSovereignty. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aConservatism.  aConstitutionalism.  aDemocracy.  aEquality.  aLiberalism.  aPopular sovereignty.  aPopulism.  aRepublicanism.  aSovereignty.  aThe People.1 aBarker, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarker, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlitz, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharette, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConti, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, Robert G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLynn, Joshua A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinkoski, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSelinger, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShell, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVaughn, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVincenzi, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilford, Heather Pangle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilford, Paul T., econtributor.4ctb4htt